definitions.definition: An indefinite , but usually small , number of.
examples: There are a few cars (= some, but a relatively small number ) in the street.
Quite a few people (= a significant number ) were pleasantly surprised.
I think he's had a few drinks.
The few cheapest hotels I could find are the farthest too.

definitions.definition: Not many ; a small (in comparison with another number stated or implied) but somewhat indefinite number of.
examples: Very few did she have not to go there, did she?
I was expecting a big crowd at the party, but very few people (= almost none ) turned up.

definitions.definition: Obscuring one to two oktas (eighths) of the sky.
examples: Tonight: A few clouds. Increasing cloudiness overnight.

definitions.definition: Having a 10 percent chance of measurable precipitation (0.01 inch); used interchangeably with isolated .
labels: of rainfall with regard to a location
label_groups: meteorology , of rainfall with regard to a location

main_definition: ( preceded by another determiner ) An indefinite , but usually small , number of.
secondary_definitions: ( used alone ) Not many ; a small (in comparison with another number stated or implied) but somewhat indefinite number of.
( meteorology , of clouds ) Obscuring one to two oktas (eighths) of the sky.
( meteorology , of rainfall with regard to a location ) (US?) Having a 10 percent chance of measurable precipitation (0.01 inch); used interchangeably with isolated .
